Clustering based on survey data of a running footwear & apparel company¶

Objective¶

To group the customers of a running footwear & apparel company based on the inputs collected through a survey

Team Members¶

  • Collaborated with 'Kranthi Kumar kotrika' for Similarity Metrics calculation.

Data Preprocessing¶

  • We do not really requrie scaling or normalization here as all the coulmns in the data has only binary values
  • Remove columns - 'record', 'id' - [0, 1] columns
  • Remove 'country' related columns - [2,3,4] columns - because the clustering we are trying to do here is to understand the preferences of shoe or apparel for an idividual and I assume that does not depend on which country they belong to
  • Remove 'verification' related columns - [5, 6] and consider only verified participants

Similarty Metrics¶

I am considering Jaccard distance to calculate and measure the similarity in the data. The reason to choose Jaccard distance is:

  • Binary Data: The dataset consists primarily of binary (0/1) attributes, making Jaccard similarity especially relevant.

  • Set-Based Comparison: Jaccard similarity compares the intersection versus the union of the attributes, ideal for binary sets.

In [18]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist, squareform

# Calculating the pairwise Jaccard distances
jaccard_distances = pdist(data_processed, metric='jaccard')

# Converting the distances to a square matrix form
jaccard_similarity = squareform(1 - jaccard_distances)  # Converting distances to similarity

# If you want to put this into a DataFrame for better readability:
jaccard_similarity_df = pd.DataFrame(jaccard_similarity, index=data_processed.index, columns=data_processed.index)

from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram, linkage

# Generate the linkage matrix
Z = linkage(jaccard_distances, 'ward')

# Plot the dendrogram
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
dendrogram(Z, labels=data_processed.index)
plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel('Distance')
plt.show()

Observations:

  • From the Dendogram which is plotted based on Jacarrd distances, we can clearly see that there are 3 groups or clusters in a broad sense.
  • If we further look down, we can see that there are 2 major groups within the first cluster (colored in orange)
  • But, overall 3 clusters is a good split as interpreted from the dendogram

Model building¶

K-Means Clustering¶

In [21]:
#Empty dictionary to store the SSE for each value of k
sse = {}

# iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm. Use inertia attribute from the clustering object and
# store the inertia value for that k
for k in range(1, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1).fit(data_processed)
    sse[k] = kmeans.inertia_

#Elbow plot
plt.figure()
plt.plot(list(sse.keys()), list(sse.values()), 'bx-')
plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")
plt.ylabel("SSE")
plt.show()

Observations:

  • We can see a slight elbow bend at k = 3
In [22]:
#Empty dictionary to store the Silhouette score for each value of k
sc = {}

# iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm. Store the Silhouette score for that k
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1).fit(data_processed)
    labels = kmeans.predict(data_processed)
    sc[k] = silhouette_score(data_processed, labels)

#Elbow plot
plt.figure()
plt.plot(list(sc.keys()), list(sc.values()), 'bx-')
plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.show()

Observations:

  • We can see the highest silhouette score for k = 3
In [23]:
# Getting the k value with highest silhouette_score
silh_dict = {}
for s in range(2,10):
  k_test = KMeans(n_clusters=s, n_init='auto', random_state=50).fit(data_processed)
  score = silhouette_score(data_processed, k_test.labels_)
# Print the score
  print(f'Silhouette Score of {s} is : {score.round(4)}') #rounding the value to 4 decimal places
  silh_dict[s] = score #
  #print(silh_dict)
silh_max = max(silh_dict, key = silh_dict.get)
silh_max_value =  max(silh_dict.values()) #best k value based on the score
print(f'k value {silh_max} has the highest silhoutte score value : {silh_max_value} compared to other k values')

Comparison¶

  • We can see that k-means and Gaussian clustering methods have similar grouping in terms of the number of records or data points in each cluster.
  • I pick kmeans just beacuse it is a simpler and less complex algorithm

Insights and Recommendations¶

From Kmeans clusters we have seen that

  • Group-1 are from age groups - Under 18, 18-24; group-2 are from age groups 25-34, group-0 are from 35-44.
  • Group - 0
    • age 35-44
    • 3+ pairs of running shoes, some that I use for training and others that I use to race.
    • 5+ pairs of running shoes depending on the type of training and racing that I'm doing.
  • Group - 1
    • age Under 18, 18-24

  • Group - 2

    • age 25-34

  • It looks like age group is a driving factor for people behaviours and purchases, I would recommend the company teams to analyze more on how different other characteristics of these groups are and how they are buying

  • They can design marketing things based on those specific charactyeristics and broadly on age groups.
  • Also, if there is more data to analyze we can interpret the behaviour more well. So, would recommend the company to also collect more data
